The Exercise Premise
These exercises — and the way we review them — are grounded in a core belief: code and the artifacts produced in a software engineering workflow are the most reliable, enduring, and objective way to communicate concepts, practices, ideas, and intent. Commit messages, pull request descriptions, documentation, test coverage, and architectural decisions all tell a rich and verifiable story about how an engineer thinks, solves problems, and collaborates.

We believe this approach is meaningfully better than traditional synchronous, verbal interview techniques. Live interviews rely heavily on the interpersonal rapport established between an applicant and a reviewer in a brief window of time. They are susceptible to a wide range of cognitive biases — from anchoring and confirmation bias to the halo effect. They are time-intensive for both parties, difficult to reproduce consistently across candidates, and produce evidence that can be clouded by factors entirely unrelated to engineering ability: stress levels, interview timing, environmental distractions, and the inherent pressure of real-time performance.

The asynchronous model addresses these shortcomings directly. It allows an applicant to work on their own schedule, in an environment where they are most productive, and with the tools and resources they use every day. It equally allows one or more reviewers to evaluate the output independently, thoughtfully, and on their own time — unconstrained by scheduling conflicts or the pressures of a live conversation. The result is a fairer, more thorough, and more representative evaluation of the work an engineer is capable of producing.

Please structure and approach the exercises with this premise in mind. Let the work speak for itself — through clean, well-organized code; meaningful commit history; clear documentation; and thoughtful engineering decisions.

