AI-assisted Coding
You are not only allowed to use AI-assisted development techniques when preparing your exercise submissions — you are actively encouraged to do so. The practice of software engineering has changed fundamentally. Reviewers at Lockbox AI understand this, and our evaluation reflects it. We are not looking for evidence that you can write boilerplate from memory. We are looking for evidence that you know how to leverage the full capability of your toolchain to produce better outcomes, faster.

Consider committing the artifacts of your AI-assisted workflow directly to the repository you submit. These artifacts are informative and tell a meaningful story about how you work:

CLAUDE.md, .cursor/rules/ — agent guidance and project conventions you defined to shape model behavior
Skills and agent definitions — reusable automation you built to accelerate the workflow
Intermediate planning documents — architectural notes, decision records, or design drafts produced during the process
MCP configurations — if you used non-proprietary MCP tools, include your mcp.json so reviewers can see the surface area you connected to
What reviewers want to see is the portion of the workflow that genuinely required you — your judgment, your taste, your architectural instincts, your ability to identify what matters. Show how you used the tooling to eliminate rote, mechanical implementation details. Show how you stayed at the top of your license: doing only the work that truly requires a skilled human in the loop, and delegating everything else. That is the signal we are looking for.

Use Commit History to Demonstrate Experimentation and Failed Directions
Nothing of genuine interest in software development is produced without first navigating a landscape of competing options — many of which dead-end. The instinct to hide that navigation, to present only a clean linear history of correct decisions, is understandable. Resist it. The path you took matters as much as where you landed.

Spike. Investigate an approach that seems promising and push it until it breaks or reveals its limits. Explore the alternative that the obvious solution forecloses. Commit those experiments — even the ones you back out. A revert commit with a clear message explaining why the approach was abandoned is more informative than a pristine history that implies the first idea was always the right one.

Reviewers read commit histories the way editors read drafts: not looking for perfection, but looking for evidence of a thinking process. A history that shows you pushed on the edges, recognized a wrong turn, articulated what you learned, and resolved on a better path is a far richer signal of engineering judgment than one that was reverse-engineered after the fact to look tidy. Let the repository tell the honest story of how the work got done.

Submitting an Exercise
You may share a completed exercise with the Lockbox AI team via either a public or private repository — the choice is yours. Each starter repository includes scripts that support both workflows.

If you opt for a private repository, please add jpfulton-lockboxai as a contributor so the team can pull a local clone of your submission. Once you receive a confirmation email from join@lockboxai.com confirming the clone was successful, you are welcome to revoke access at that time.

When you are ready to submit, send an email to join@lockboxai.com with the following: a link to your repository, the exercise ID as specified in the exercise document, and any additional context you would like to provide.

